# Neurotonics repository rules

This repository contains the Neurotonics ecommerce storefront, checkout/CMS
backend, and admin dashboard. Before making changes, read the relevant files in
this repo and follow the patterns already in use.

## Project shape

- Storefront: `src/` is a Next.js 16 App Router application with React 19,
  TypeScript, Tailwind CSS 4, and static export configured in `next.config.ts`.
- Backend: `server/` is a CommonJS Express 4 application that creates Stripe
  checkout/payment flows, serves the CMS API, handles webhooks, sends email, and
  serves the built admin SPA.
- Admin UI: `server/admin-ui/` is a Vite + React + TypeScript app. Its built
  output is committed under `server/public/admin/`.
- Content source: storefront copy and product/shipping data live in
  `src/content/*.json`; CMS routes can commit changes to these files and trigger
  a GitHub Pages rebuild.
- Runtime data: CMS data uses SQLite via `server/db.js`. Do not commit
  `server/data/`, local SQLite files, backups, or secrets.

## Next.js 16 rule

This is not the legacy Next.js API surface. Before editing Next.js app code,
read the relevant guide in `node_modules/next/dist/docs/`. If dependencies are
not installed, run `npm ci` first. Pay attention to static export constraints:
the production storefront is built to `out/` and deployed to GitHub Pages with
`basePath: "/neurotonics"` and unoptimized images.

## Commands

Root storefront:

```bash
npm ci
npm run dev
npm run build
npm run lint
npm test
```

Backend:

```bash
cd server
npm ci
npm run dev
npm start
npm run build:admin
```

Admin UI source:

```bash
cd server/admin-ui
npm ci
npm run dev
npm run build
npm run lint
```

## Implementation guidance

- Prefer existing helpers: cart state in `src/lib/cart.tsx`, shipping logic in
  `src/lib/shipping.ts`, checkout persistence in `src/lib/checkoutState.ts` and
  `src/lib/shippingState.ts`, backend DB helpers in `server/db.js`, and auth
  middleware in `server/auth.js`.
- Keep product pricing validation server-side. The Express server has an
  authorised `PRODUCT_CATALOG`; update it when product prices change.
- Preserve checkout security controls: validate carts, sanitize redirects,
  avoid trusting client-supplied totals, and keep Stripe secret keys server-side.
- Stripe webhooks must be mounted before `express.json()` because signature
  verification requires the raw body.
- CMS routes should require `requireAuth`; admin-only routes should also use
  `requireRole("admin")`.
- Do not manually edit generated admin assets unless intentionally updating the
  built admin bundle. Prefer editing `server/admin-ui/src/` and rebuilding.
- Avoid unrelated refactors. Keep changes scoped and add or update tests when
  touching cart, shipping, checkout validation, API routes, auth, or DB logic.

## Environment and deployment

- Storefront deploys to GitHub Pages through `.github/workflows/deploy.yml`.
- CMS content rebuilds are triggered by `.github/workflows/cms-rebuild.yml`.
- The CMS server is deployed on Render using `render.yaml`; `autoDeploy` is
  intentionally disabled.
- Required runtime secrets include Stripe keys, CMS JWT secrets, email provider
  settings, and GitHub PAT settings. Never commit real values.

